  "target_response": {
    "text": "Train, but not legs at full tilt. Recovery at 64% is mid-range, your HRV of 57 ms sits right near your baseline of about 59 ms, and you slept 6.9 hours — nothing there says stand down. Quad soreness two days after heavy squats is normal muscle repair, not damage; the classic sign is that it's tender to touch and eases as you warm up. My call: a moderate session today — upper body or easy zone-two cardio both work, and light cycling or walking will actually help the quads loosen. Hit legs again once the soreness has clearly faded. The line to watch is different pain: sharp, one-sided, joint-centered, or worsening as you move — that isn't soreness and deserves getting checked, whereas an even, dull ache in both quads is exactly what productive training feels like.",
